<exercises xml:id="exercises-pred-logic">
<title>Exercises</title>

<exercisegroup cols="2">
	<title>Interpreting symbolic language</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
		Let <m>A(x)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>x</m> is a wonderful learning experience</q>,
		where <m>x</m> is a free variable in the domain of all university courses.
		</p>
		<p> Translate each of the following into an English sentence that is grammatically correct. </p>
	</introduction>
	<exercise><p> <m>A(\text{AUMAT 250})</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists x)A(x)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall x)A(x)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>\lgcnot (\forall x)A(x)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists x)\lgcnot A(x)</m> </p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup>
	<title>Translating into symbolic language</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
		Let <m>B(x)</m> represent the predicate <q><m>x</m> is excellent</q>,
		where <m>x</m> is a free variable in the domain of all Augustana professors.
		</p>
		<p> Translate each of the following into symbolic language. </p>
	</introduction>
	<exercise><p> The instructor for this course is an excellent professor. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Every professor at your university is excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Some professor at your university is excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Some professors at your university are excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> There is at least one professor at your university who is excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Some professor at your university is not excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Some professors at your university are not excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> Any professor at your university is excellent. </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> No professor at your university is excellent. </p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup>
	<title>Analyzing predicate statements about integers</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
		Let <m>P(m,n)</m> represent the predicate <m>2m - 45n > 101</m>,
		where <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are free variables in the domain of integers.
		</p><p>
		For each of the following, determine whether the statement is true or false.
		Explain your reasoning.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<exercise><p> <m>P(25,-1)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>P(30,-1)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>P(100,2)\lgcor P(100,3)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>P(100,2) \lgcand P(100,3)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists m)(\exists n) P(m,n)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall m)(\forall n) P(m,n)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall m)(\exists n) P(m,n)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists m)(\forall n) P(m,n)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall m)(\exists q)(\forall n)(P(q,n)\lgccond P(m,n))</m> </p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercisegroup>
	<title>Analyzing predicate statements about functions</title>
	<introduction>
		<p>
		<em>(Requires calculus.)</em>
		Let <m>P(f,g)</m> represent the predicate <m>\frac{df}{dx} = g</m>,
		where <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are free variables in the domain of <em>continuous</em> functions in the real variable <m>x</m>.
		</p><p>
		For each of the following, determine whether the statement is true or false.
		Explain your reasoning.
		</p>
	</introduction>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists f)(\exists g) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall f)(\forall g) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall f)(\exists g) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists f)(\forall g) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\forall g)(\exists f) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
	<exercise><p> <m>(\exists g)(\forall f) P(f,g)</m> </p></exercise>
</exercisegroup>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-pred-logic-english-to-symbols">
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::pred.logic::english.to.symbols} -->
	<introduction><p>
		Consider the statement <q>every odd number is either <m>1</m> more or <m>3</m> more than a mulitple of <m>4</m>.</q>
		<!-- %\begin{inlinenote}This statement appears in a Worked Example on page \pageref{WEXAMPLE::every.odd.1.or.3.mod.4}.\end{inlinenote} -->
		<!-- TODO Huh? what is this old note above ? -->
	</p></introduction>
	<task><p> Assign appropriate predicates (with domains explictly stated), and then translate the statement into symbolic logic. </p></task>
	<task xml:id="exercise-pred-logic-english-to-symbols-negate"><p>
		<!-- \label{EXERCISE::pred.logic::english.to.symbols::negate} -->
		Negate the statement, and simplify the logical expression so that any/all negation symbols appear directly to the left of a predicate.
	</p></task>
	<task><p>
			Translate your simplified negated statement
			from <xref ref="exercise-pred-logic-english-to-symbols-negate" text="type-local" />
			into English.
	</p></task>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="exercise-pred-logic-multivar-predicate-to-english"> <!-- TODO add note that this exercise requires calculus -->
	<!-- \label{EXERCISE::pred.logic::multivar.predicate.to.english} -->
	<introduction><p>
		Let <m>P(f,g)</m> represent the predicate <m>\frac{df}{dx} = g</m>,
		and let <m>E(f,g)</m> represent the predicate <m>g = f</m>,
		where <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> are free variables in the domain of functions in the real variable <m>x</m>.
		Consider the statement
		<md> (\forall f)(\forall g)\Bbrac{(\exists h)\bbrac{P(f,h) \lgcand P(g,h)} \lgccond E(f,g)} </md>.
	</p></introduction>
	<task xml:id="exercise-pred-logic-multivar-predicate-to-english-to-english"><p>
		<!-- \label{EXERCISE::pred.logic::multivar.predicate.to.english::to.english} -->
		Translate the statement into English.
	</p></task>
	<task><p> Determine whether the statement is true. </p></task>
	<task xml:id="exercise-pred-logic-multivar-predicate-to-english-negate"><p>
		<!-- \label{EXERCISE::pred.logic::multivar.predicate.to.english::negate} -->
		Working with the originally provided symbolic version above,
		negate the statement.
		Simplify the negated version to so that any/all negation symbols appear directly to the left of one of the predicates <m>P</m> or <m>E</m>.
	</p></task>
	<task><p>
		Translate your simplified negated statement
		from <xref ref="exercise-pred-logic-multivar-predicate-to-english-negate" text="type-local">Part</xref>
		into English.
	</p></task>
</exercise>

<exercise>
	<statement>
		<p>
		You've become an expert at predicate logic, and now make a (very meagre) living grading logic assignments for a large university.
		Here is the question you've been assigned to mark two thousand times.
		</p>
		<blockquote>
			<p> Let <m>x</m> represent a free variable from the domain of all living humans. </p>
			<p>
			Translate the following two statements into properly quantified predicate statements in the variable <m>x</m>.
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li> All university students study diligently. </li>
				<li> Some university students study diligently. </li>
			</ol>
			</p>
		</blockquote>
		<p>
		You pick up the first assignment.
		Here is the student's answer.
		</p>
		<blockquote><p>
			Let <m>U(x)</m> mean <q><m>x</m> is a university student</q>.
			Let <m>S(x)</m> mean <q><m>x</m> studies diligently</q>.
			<ol marker="(i)">
				<li> <m>(\forall x)\bigl[ U(x) \lgccond S(x) \bigr]</m>. </li>
				<li> <m>(\exists x)\bigl[ U(x) \lgccond S(x) \bigr]</m>. </li>
			</ol>
		</p></blockquote>
		<p>
		Are the student's answers correct?
		Justify your assessment.
		</p>
	</statement>
	<hint><p>
		Try translating the student's symbolic language statements back into English,
		<em>explicitly using the stated domain of <m>x</m></em>,
		and see what you get.
	</p></hint>
</exercise>

</exercises>
